            <p>289&#45;9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/>
                Portland Or. Nov. 30&#47;87.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                Reverend &#38; Dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>On behalf of Salome &#38;<lb/> myself I wish to express<lb/> our thanks for your kind
                &#61;<lb/>ness &#38; the trouble you took<lb/> to prepare the &#34;Ketubah&#34;<lb/> which we made use of<lb/> at the wedding ceremony.<lb/></p>
            <p>We highly appreciate<lb/> the sentiment which prompted<lb/> you to perform this &#34;labor<lb/> of love&#34;; &#38; altho&#39; you in&#45;<lb/>formed David you sent it<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>as a substitute&#44; still<lb/> we could not help but<lb/> feel how much more<lb/> favored we would have<lb/> been had circumstances<lb/> permitted you to have been<lb/> present &#38; to have performed<lb/> our marriage ceremony.<lb/>  As it is&#44; it will always<lb/> remain one of Salomes<lb/> ungratified wishes that<lb/> her marriage ceremony was<lb/> not performed by her<lb/> cherished and esteemed friend<lb/> For myself&#44; altho unacquainted<lb/> with you&#44; except through hearsay<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>I shall always share in<lb/> the regret that distance<lb/> &#38; circumstances conspired<lb/> to make your presence impossible<lb/> At some time I trust it may<lb/> or my good fortune to learn<lb/> to know you &#38; yours.<lb/></p>
            <p>Salome joins me in again<lb/> thanking you for what you have<lb/> done &#38; especially for the kindly<lb/> interest you have manifested<lb/> in her &#38; our welfares.<lb/></p>
            <p>Together we can only say we appreciate it.<lb/>  With greetings from Salome &#38; myself<lb/> Believe me<lb/> very sincerely &#38; respectfully<lb/> your obedient servant<lb/> Alex Bernstein<lb/></p>
            </body>
